Creating a Discord bot with a ban command using Discord.js v14 involves several steps, including setting up your bot application on Discord's Developer Portal, installing Discord.js, and writing the code for the bot. Below is a basic example of how you can create such a bot. Note that you need Node.js installed to use Discord.js and you must have set up a bot application on the Discord Developer Portal and invited the bot to your server with the appropriate permissions.

First, ensure you have Discord.js v14 installed in your project:
```
npm install discord.js@14
```

Then, create a file named `bot.js` (or another name of your choosing) and add the following code:

```javascript
const { Client, GatewayIntentBits, REST, SlashCommandBuilder, Routes } = require('discord.js');
const { token, clientId, guildId } = require('./config.json'); // Ensure you have a config.json file with your bot's token, clientId, and guildId

const commands = [
  new SlashCommandBuilder()
    .setName('ban')
    .setDescription('Bans a user from the server.')
    .addUserOption(option => option.setName('target').setDescription('The user to ban').setRequired(true))
    .addStringOption(option => option.setName('reason').setDescription('The reason for the ban').setRequired(false)),
]
  .map(command => command.toJSON());

const rest = new REST({ version: '10' }).setToken(token);

(async () => {
  try {
    console.log('Started refreshing application (/) commands.');

    await rest.put(
      Routes.applicationGuildCommands(clientId, guildId),
      { body: commands },
    );

    console.log('Successfully reloaded application (/) commands.');
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
  }
})();

const client = new Client({ intents: [GatewayIntentBits.Guilds] });

client.once('ready', () => {
  console.log('Ready!');
});

client.on('interactionCreate', async interaction => {
  if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

  const { commandName } = interaction;

  if (commandName === 'ban') {
    const user = interaction.options.getUser('target');
    const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason') || 'No reason provided';
    const member = interaction.guild.members.cache.get(user.id);

    if (!member) {
      await interaction.reply({ content: 'User not found in this server.', ephemeral: true });
      return;
    }

    try {
      await member.ban({ reason });
      await interaction.reply({ content: `Successfully banned ${user.tag} for: ${reason}`, ephemeral: false });
    } catch (error) {
      console.error(error);
      await interaction.reply({ content: 'I was unable to ban the user.', ephemeral: true });
    }
  }
});

client.login(token);
```

Important points:
- Ensure you have a `config.json` file in your project directory or another method of securely managing your bot's `token`, `clientId`, and `guildId`.
- This example code demonstrates a basic implementation of a ban command as a slash command for a single guild. For global commands or additional command options, further modifications are necessary.
- You must have the `BAN_MEMBERS` permission in the Discord guild to ban members.

This code snippet outlines the setup of a Discord bot capable of banning a user from the server with an optional reason, all done through Discord.js v14 using slash commands.

Here's a simple C++ function that performs a basic transformation of Markdown formatted text to HTML. This function only handles two common Markdown features: headings defined by a leading '#' character and paragraphs separated by empty lines. More sophisticated Markdown features like bold, italic, links, lists, etc., are not covered by this basic example.

Please note that a full Markdown to HTML converter would be quite complex and likely exceed the 600-500 word range. This is a simplified version.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <sstream>
#include <string>

std::string MarkdownToHTML(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::istringstream stream(markdown);
    std::string html, line;
    bool inParagraph = false;

    while (std::getline(stream, line)) {
        if (line.empty()) {
            if (inParagraph) {
                html += "</p>\n";
                inParagraph = false;
            }
        } else {
            // Check for headings.
            if (line[0] == '#') {
                size_t headingLevel = 0;
                while (line[headingLevel] == '#' && headingLevel < line.size()) {
                    headingLevel++;
                }

                if (line[headingLevel] == ' ') {
                    // Trim the markdown heading syntax and wrap in HTML tags.
                    std::string headingText = line.substr(headingLevel + 1);
                    html += "<h" + std::to_string(headingLevel) + ">" + headingText + "</h" + std::to_string(headingLevel) + ">\n";
                } else {
                    // Incorrectly formatted heading. Treat it as a paragraph.
                    if (!inParagraph) {
                        html += "<p>";
                        inParagraph = true;
                    }
                    html += line + "\n";
                }
            } else {
                // No heading, so start or continue a paragraph.
                if (!inParagraph) {
                    html += "<p>";
                    inParagraph = true;
                }
                html += line + "\n";
            }
        }
    }

    // Close the last paragraph tag, if there is one.
    if (inParagraph) {
        html += "</p>\n";
    }

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = 
        "# Heading Level 1\n"
        "This is a simple paragraph that is converted from markdown to HTML.\n"
        "It even supports newline characters.\n\n"
        "## Heading Level 2\n"
        "Another paragraph under a sub-heading\nto demonstrate basic conversion.";

    std::cout << MarkdownToHTML(markdown) << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

In the `MarkdownToHTML` function:
- We read the markdown text line by line.
- If a line is empty, we either close a paragraph (`<p></p>`) if we are inside one, or just ignore it.
- If a line starts with `#`, we detect headings of various levels and wrap them in `<h1></h1> ... <h6></h6>` HTML tags.
- Other lines are considered part of a paragraph, and are wrapped in `<p></p>` tags.
- We use a flag `inParagraph` to track whether we are currently inside a paragraph, so we know when to start or end one.

This code is a starting point and does not cover many aspects of Markdown, like bullet points, code blocks, emphasis, links, images, and more. Also, it is worth noting that this converter does not sanitize HTML for potential security issues such as XSS (Cross-Site Scripting), nor does it handle edge cases, so it should not be used in production without enhancements.

This example is kept simple to comply with the requested word limit and provide a basic understanding of how a Markdown to HTML conversion might be initiated in C++.

