```javascript
function checkPrimeNumbers(numbers) {
  // Helper function to check if a single number is prime
  function isPrime(num) {
    // Numbers less than 2 are not prime
    if (num < 2) return false;

    // Check divisibility from 2 to the square root of num
    for (let i = 2, sqrtNum = Math.sqrt(num); i <= sqrtNum; i++) {
      if (num % i === 0) return false;
    }

    // If no divisors were found, num is prime
    return true;
  }

  // Check each number in the input array
  numbers.forEach((num) => {
    if (isPrime(num)) {
      console.log(num); // Print prime numbers to the console
    }
  });
}

// Example usage:
checkPrimeNumbers([3, 5, 8, 13, 26]); // This should print 3, 5, and 13 to the console
```

### Explanation:

1. **Helper Function isPrime**: At the core of the `checkPrimeNumbers` function is a helper function named `isPrime`. This function takes a single number (`num`) as input and returns `true` if it's a prime number or `false` otherwise. It first checks if `num` is less than 2 since numbers less than 2 are not prime. It then uses a for loop to check if `num` is divisible by any number between 2 and the square root of `num`. If `num` is divisible by any such number, it's not prime, and `isPrime` returns `false`. Otherwise, it returns `true`.

2. **Checking Each Number**: The `checkPrimeNumbers` function iterates over each number in the provided array using the `forEach` method. For each number, it calls the `isPrime` function to check if it's prime.

3. **Printing Prime Numbers**: When the `isPrime` function returns `true` for a number, indicating the number is prime, that number is printed to the console using `console.log`.

### Remarks:

- The function is designed to work with an array of exactly 5 numbers, as per the question's requirement, but it can also work with arrays of different lengths.
- The implementation details, such as the `isPrime` helper function, ensure efficiency by reducing the range of numbers checked for divisibility to from 2 up to the square root of the number being checked. This optimization significantly decreases the number of operations needed to identify prime numbers, especially for larger values.

Below is the HTML code for a fake chatbot modal which imitates a chat history with four messages - two from the human user and two from the AI chatbot. I have also included some basic CSS for styling the modal and JavaScript to handle the opening and closing of the modal.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>Chatbot Modal</title>
<style>
/* Chat Modal Styles */
.modal {
    display: none; 
    position: fixed;
    left: 0;
    top: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    background-color: rgba(0,0,0,0.4);
    z-index: 1;
}

.modal-content {
    position: fixed;
    top: 50%;
    left: 50%;
    transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
    background-color: #fefefe;
    padding: 20px;
    border: 1px solid #888;
    width: 300px;
    border-radius: 5px;
}

.close {
    color: #aaa;
    float: right;
    font-size: 28px;
    font-weight: bold;
}

.close:hover,
.close:focus {
    color: black;
    text-decoration: none;
    cursor: pointer;
}

.chat-container {
    max-height: 200px;
    overflow-y: auto;
}

.chat-message {
    margin: 10px 0;
}

.user-message {
    text-align: left;
    color: blue;
}

.bot-message {
    text-align: right;
    color: green;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<!-- Trigger/Open The Modal -->
<button id="myBtn">Open Chat History</button>

<!-- The Modal -->
<div id="myModal" class="modal">

  <!-- Modal content -->
  <div class="modal-content">
    <span class="close">&times;</span>
    <div class="chat-container">
      <!-- User Message 1 -->
      <div class="chat-message user-message">
        User: Hi there! How can you help me?
      </div>
      <!-- Bot Message 1 -->
      <div class="chat-message bot-message">
        Bot: Hello! I can help answer questions and guide you. What do you need assistance with?
      </div>
      <!-- User Message 2 -->
      <div class="chat-message user-message">
        User: I need help with my account settings.
      </div>
      <!-- Bot Message 2 -->
      <div class="chat-message bot-message">
        Bot: Sure, I can help with that. What issue are you experiencing?
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<script>
// Get the modal
var modal = document.getElementById("myModal");

// Get the button that opens the modal
var btn = document.getElementById("myBtn");

// Get the <span> element that closes the modal
var span = document.getElementsByClassName("close")[0];

// When the user clicks the button, open the modal 
btn.onclick = function() {
    modal.style.display = "block";
}

// When the user clicks on <span> (x), close the modal
span.onclick = function() {
    modal.style.display = "none";
}

// When the user clicks anywhere outside of the modal, close it
window.onclick = function(event) {
    if (event.target == modal) {
        modal.style.display = "none";
    }
}
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

Explanation:

- The `.modal` class styles the modal background and defaults to being hidden with `display: none;`.
- Inside the modal, there is `.modal-content` that contains the actual content of the chat history and a close button (`<span class="close">&times;</span>`).
- The `.chat-container` represents the chat history area with a defined maximum height and scrollable overflow.
- Messages are contained within `.chat-message` with additional classes to differentiate between user messages (`.user-message`) and bot messages (`.bot-message`), each with different text alignment and colors.
- The JavaScript is very simple; it fetches the modal and the button elements by their respective IDs, assigns the click event to the button to show the modal, and assigns another click event to the close (span) element to hide the modal. It also adds functionality to close the modal when the user clicks outside of it.

This setup will give you a modal pop-up that shows a fake chat history with alternating messages from the user and the bot when the "Open Chat History" button is clicked. The chat can then be closed either by clicking on the close button or by clicking outside the modal area.

In TypeScript, expressing to the type system that you are confident a value will only ever have one type, even though it may theoretically have multiple types, can be achieved through a technique called "type assertion". This allows you to override the inferred type and tell TypeScript that you want to treat a variable as a different type.

Type assertions are like a type cast in other languages, but they perform no special checking or restructuring of data. They're a way for you to tell the TypeScript compiler to trust you about the type of something, without forcing it to validate.

Here is an example of how to use type assertions in TypeScript:

```typescript
let someValue: any = "this is a string";

// Use a type assertion to tell TypeScript that someValue is definitely a string.
let strLength: number = (someValue as string).length;
```

Or alternatively, using the "angle-bracket" syntax:

```typescript
let strLength: number = (<string>someValue).length;
```

Both examples will compile to the same JavaScript. However, the "as" syntax is generally preferred when using JSX with React, because the angle-bracket syntax can be confused with JSX.

Type assertion should be used with caution because it overrides the compiler's type checking, which can lead to runtime errors if your assumption about the type is incorrect.

Another approach to ensuring a variable has a single type when multiple are possible is to use type guards. Type guards are runtime checks that ensure the type of a variable within a conditional block. Here's an example:

```typescript
function example(value: string | number) {
  if (typeof value === "string") {
    // Inside this block, value is treated as a string
    console.log(value.substr(0, 2));
  } else {
    // Inside this block, value is treated as a number
    console.log(value.toFixed(2));
  }
}
```

In the example above, TypeScript understands the type of `value` within each branch of the `if` statement, due to the `typeof` guard. There are also `instanceof` guards for checking an object's constructor, and custom type guard functions can be defined that perform more complex checks.

Another pattern you might use when you know more about the value's type than TypeScript can infer is called "narrowing" or "refinement". for instance, after you validated an input:

```typescript
function process(input: string | number) {
  if (!isValid(input)) {
    throw new Error("Invalid input");
  }

  // From this point onwards, TypeScript knows that `input` is not just a `string | number`.
  // It's a `string | number` that is valid according to your `isValid` function.
  // You can then use type assertion if you're certain about the specific type.
  let refinedInput = input as string; // If you are sure it's a string after validation
  // ... do something with refinedInput
}
```

In summary, to tell TypeScript that a value will definitely have a specific type, you can use type assertions with `as` or angle-brackets. However, you should leverage these with care, and type guards and refinement patterns may offer safer and more maintainable ways to inform the TypeScript type checker about the types you're working with.

